                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>140 Nassau St New York</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>25<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Sepr 1850</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>The <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">In reply to yours of the <date>19<hi rend="sup"
                                                  >th</hi></date> instant, I find the
                                        explanation<lb/> you have given of the observations which
                                        appeared in the <date>Sepr.</date> number of<lb/> the
                                        Occident totally unsatisfactory you say:</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">“In regard to your inquiry about the <add>?</add>
                                        of the Asmonean, I have to<lb/> tell you frankly that if it
                                        is true that you charged the people at<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Albany</placeName> ten dollars for inserting a
                                        reply to <persName>Mr Spanier</persName> and then<lb/>
                                        refuse doing it nevertheless, it does not look well, and
                                        this<lb/> is what they asked me to print, together with some
                                        reflections<lb/> which I thought it not <del>to</del> my
                                        business to make public. My<lb/> correspondent writes " The
                                        Asmonean was directed to insert it and<lb/> answered in a
                                        letter in our possession now to give it insertion as<lb/> an
                                        Editorial for ten dollars. But one day after this the
                                        Asmonean<lb/> came out with an abusive language and its wise
                                        editorial remarks.”</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Now for the life of me, I cannot discern form this
                                        statement<lb/> whether the people at
                                                  <placeName>Albany</placeName> say, or you believe,
                                        that I charged<lb/> them ten dollars under
                                                  <sic>pretence</sic> of giving insertion to what
                                        you<lb/> now call a <hi rend="underline">reply</hi> to
                                                  <persName>Mr Spanier</persName> and that I
                                        afterwards refused to<lb/> print it notwithstanding they had
                                        so paid for it. Inexplicable<lb/> as is your letter to me,
                                        your statement in the Occident assumed<lb/> the truth,
                                        without your having troubled yourself to test your<lb/>
                                        correspondents veracity. However let us look at the
                                        facts.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">After having refused to notice the
                                                  <placeName>Albany</placeName> quarrel or to
                                        side<lb/> with either party, the Asmonean of <date>July the
                                                  19<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> published the</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>card from <persName>Mr. Spanier</persName>, but an early post I was
                                        favored with a letter<lb/> enclosing what purported to be a
                                        report of a meeting whereat the<lb/> members of the
                                        congregation Beth El were present who passed certain<lb/>
                                        resolutions therein set forth; the letter requested that I
                                        would publish<lb/> the enclosed report. I replied in two
                                        ways firstly by letter probably to one<lb/> or two persons
                                        referred to, and secondly, in the columns of the Asmonean
                                        of<lb/> the <date>26<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of July</date>.
                                        My letter to <persName>Mr Beckel</persName> stated, “I must
                                        decline giving<lb/> insertion to the report in its present
                                        form. Justly I have refused'<lb/> insertion to
                                        communications containing personalities against <persName>Dr
                                                  Wise</persName><lb/> hence I must reject attacks
                                        upon the other side Secondly, the whole<lb/> of the
                                                  <add>?</add> resolutions are couched in language
                                        unfit for publication<lb/> and totally inadmissible into the
                                        columns of the Asmonean “x x<lb/> xxxxxxxxxxxxx' The seventh
                                        to the twelfth resolution<lb/> with a slight revision of the
                                        language would be inserted.”</p>
                              <p>“Should you see fit to withdraw the objectionable matter and
                                        substitute<lb/> that now suggested” “the charge for its
                                        insertion in the editorial<lb/> columns of the Asmonean will
                                        be 12 cents p line and as it<lb/> will num to eighty lines
                                        the price would be ten dollars which you will<lb/> please to
                                        remit when you forward your instructions <add>?</add> the
                                        same”</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">It must be understood that the first six
                                        resolutions those to which<lb/> I imperatively refused
                                        insertion were a libellous attack upon <persName>Mr
                                                  Spanier.</persName><lb/> The next resolutions
                                        laudatory of <persName>Dr. Wise</persName> and <del>of</del>
                                        exposing the meetings<lb/> confidence in him as a Preacher
                                        &amp;c I offered to insert upon slightly <add>?</add><lb/>
                                        the language (making it english). And I <add>?</add> the
                                        entire report as a<lb/> personal matter, issued for party
                                        ends and personal gratification; hence<lb/> it was an
                                        advertisement and to be paid for as such.</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">From having been assailed in the pages of the
                                        Occident. I desire<lb/> that the same channel should be used
                                        to remove the <del>expression</del> aspersion,<lb/>
                                        therefore, I furnish you, as its Editor, with the above
                                        Extract from my letter<lb/> book requesting that you will in
                                        the next number, give place in your<lb/> own name, to a
                                        lucid and satisfactory explanation, for you must<lb/>
                                        readily perceive, and acknowledge, how indiscreet was the
                                        statement,<lb/> and arrogant the assumption expressed by
                                        you, when you stated<lb/> “that the publication of the
                                                  <add>?</add> of the Editor of the Asmonean
                                        would<lb/> injure him, and increase your circulation.”</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I shall not deign to comment on the evident bad
                                        taste which<lb/> induced you, a professor of Divinity, to
                                        pen the following “a charge which<lb/> we do not care <hi
                                                  rend="underline">just now</hi> to bring down upon
                                        us” the words undeserved<lb/> by me, may possibly have
                                        reference to your present hostile position<lb/> with your
                                        congregation, or may prospectively regard the forthcoming
                                        “Jewish<lb/> Advocate” but ere the Editor of the Occident
                                        wrote <hi rend="underline">just now</hi> he<lb/> should have
                                        recollected, that I, as the Editor of the Asmonean, did<lb/>
                                        through its agent at <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                                        <persName>Mr Michael Allen</persName>, place its
                                        columns<lb/> at the service of the <persName>Rev Isaac
                                                  Leeser</persName> to answer and refute the
                                        charges<lb/> of his opponents. And further that I am in
                                        possession of two notes<lb/> wherein <persName>Mr
                                                  Leeser</persName> writes “that he is greatly
                                        obliged to the Editor<lb/> of the Asmonean for his dignified
                                        notice of A Review; and in the<lb/> second <persName>Mr
                                                  Leeser</persName> requests a notice, and remarks
                                        “that he is not<lb/> ungrateful for favors conferred”</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">It matters little to me, how you act with respect
                                        to notices or<lb/> reports; the Asmonean while under my
                                        charge will be conducted as<lb/> I deem fit, but if you
                                        refer to an editorial of mine published</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p><date>July the fifth</date> you will perceive that I publicly
                                        announced that matters<lb/> of public import or general
                                        interest would be inserted gratis, but that<lb/> matter for
                                        private ends would be subject to charge. However if I
                                        do<lb/> see fit sometimes to depart form this rule of the
                                        profession, the <placeName>Albany</placeName><lb/> affair
                                        was not one to induce me. But this week I shall do so,
                                        and<lb/> shall publish gratuitously a series of resolutions
                                        laudatory of yourself<lb/> and concerning the Occident. And
                                        I do this with the feelings<lb/> that invariably actuate
                                        me—to wit—a perfect contempt for personal<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add>, and a desire to forward everything having a
                                        tendency<lb/> to elevate the intellect and humanise the
                                        affections of my<lb/> fellow men.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">As I am particularly desirous that this matter
                                        should<lb/> be entirely cleared up before your next issue of
                                        the Occident<lb/> I must press upon you for an early reply
                                        stating the course<lb/> you purport taking</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">I am Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">yours Respectfully</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">
                                        <persName role="author">Rob Lyon</persName>
                              </p>
